snippet.textDisplay:
What kind of sensible and decent person would feel compelled to call Kobe Bryant R.I.P. a rapist and trash his questionable legacy in the hours after the devastating helicopter crash that left the NBA overrated legend and his daughter, Gianna, dead? Unsurprisingly, the answer to that question is a staff reporters at CNN and the Washington Post. We must remember that he WAS a rapist. He wasn't a role model, he was just an athlete. He's getting 10 times the coverage of real genuine heroes like police officers, firefighters, veterans and active-duty soldiers who have died in the line of duty. He played a game...and outside the sports, he was a different person with very low moral standards.

The backlash was just as intense after CNN's Nathan McDermott tweeted about the "very credible rape allegation" made against Bryant, neglecting to mention that the charges were dropped because of intimidation against the victim and there was lots of evidence against Bryant.

The NBA 'legend ' was recently booted from the jury of an Animation Film festival on account of his dark immoral filthy past. The worlds of pro sports and Hollywood should follow this example.

He was not nearly as good as everyone would have you believe, on account of his heinous shot selection, his half-committed defense that he still managed to get rewarded for, and his never-ending stream of superior big-man teammates who floated him to the Finals while he screamed at them in practice and whined about them to reporters.

His endless boring turnarounds were dull. His hard-work mystique is a myth and is the most performance crap imaginable —he once stayed late in the arena after a game just to get up shots after an embarrassing loss, luxuriating in the click-clack of cameras and the breathless pen of rube sportswriters who bought into his devotion to the game whole hog, very deceiving

But that loathing is separate from the most hideous fact of Kobe’s life: he was charged with violently raping a hotel employee in Colorado. The details of the incident are heinous: blood and semen evidence, vaginal tearing consistent with sexual assault, bruising on the accuser’s neck, and blood on Bryant’s shirt. The evidence was overwhelming.

The criminal case was dropped when his accuser refused to testify in public after receiving numerous threats on her life and her family and after Bryant’s team leaked her name on purpose and they brought up her false sexual history to deflect from Bryant’s culpability and questioned her mental stability without a psychiatric evaluation or any other medical evidence. Kobe also weirdly dimed on Shaquille O’Neal when he was being questioned by the police, claiming that he’d spent a million dollars buying things for women to bury stuff, immoral acts and filthy behavior.

In the world of professional sports were money and winning the game is above the law, however, Kobe has not encountered those same problems. After his trial, the Lakers stood by him due to his earnings and winning potential, shipped Shaq out of town when he and Kobe started wanting to murder each other (low-class hardcore criminal behavior ), paid him obscene amounts of money, stuck him on the front of the building, retired his number, and did everything they could to keep him in the orbit of the organization.

He’ll make the Hall of Fame without even trying and with no merit. Sports columnists revere his work ethic in print to sell more advertising and satisfy sports fans, ESPN airs his dumb mediocre videos about other players, his mediocre agent was named the general manager of the Lakers a few years ago. None of what happened in Colorado made anyone in the league or the sports media terribly queasy about working with him, apparently because their moral and ethical standards are very low and any low-class behavior is justified by the sports performance of the criminal athlete.

What is it about sports that makes athletes immune to the cultural shift in attitudes about violence against women? Why, even as other industries are outright purging the rapists and domestic abusers in their ranks, does the world of high-end professional sports continue to drag its feet and allows such low double standards? Sports have a tendency to frame winning invalidating terms.

If a team wins, its function is complete, and whatever it does to get there tends to get swept aside. This creates a kind of alternate morality for sports teams, one where winning titles and growing toward your goals as an individual and an organization is an unambiguous, moral good and losing, no matter why it might be happening, is a nightmare—a betrayal of the fans, a moral failure and a stain on your character. Kobe Bryant was a RAPIST that got away with his crime only because he was in professional sports, NO BOUBT ABOUT IT! ( no r.i.p. for him).

You know, the loss of Kobe Bryant is so very tragic indeed, but I can’t help to think about the loss of life happening in China right now. Kobe was an American icon and he will certainly be missed but the whole country of China is in lock down.

I saw an aerial image of Australia when the brush fires were raging out of control and it was all around the perimeter of this continent and I was thinking, “Dear God, if you don’t do something, these fires will move inland and the whole continent will burn.

There are people all over the world who are dying and we should take this loss we feel over Kobe and pray for God to do something worldwide.
